                <img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/e21eaa869a1f594934019932acada3ba?s=32&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D32&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-32 photo' height='32' width='32' />				<h4 class="commentauthor"><a class="commentnum" href="#comment-473">30</a><a href='http://www.thenapkin.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Zach Katkin</a></h4>
					
				<div class="commentmetadata">December 29th, 2006 at 11:30 am</div>

				<blockquote><p>If youve got to convince visitors to sign up for your killer app, giving away FREE accounts surely cant hurt. Most Web 2.0 sites devote prime real estate to the message that they offer a free service. If that message can appear inside of the ubiquitous starburst, all the better.</p></blockquote>
<p>LOL, I am definitely guilty of that one. </p>
<p>Something beautiful just catches and everyone runs with it. I think we will slowly start to see a shift as the above outlined elements are already starting to feel dated and overly used. Fashion and design seasons aside, most of the Web 2.0 elements are for the better, the easy to read text, bright, well contrasted colors, really aid in promoting a positive experience for the user.</p>
				
